<br>
Weight gain / loss has to do with a change of diet. In my prior post I provided a couple reasons why an average football player may lose, or gain weight during the course of the season.  I illustrated this as you made a point that many similarities can be found in looking at a star QB and someone that plays EverQuest.<br>
<br>
An EverQuest player:<br>
-1. less dependence on quality food, seeks quick accessible food: i.e. potato chips, pizza, Chinese delivery.<br>
-a. Eating manufactured foods like the examples above coupled with little to no exercise (most people sit in their chairs) one can expect to gain weight.<br>
<br>
If we have an EverQuest player, that plays more than 30 hours a week while in a resting position and consuming food quantities with little to no exercise, then one can expect that individual to gain weight over a period of time.<br>
<br>
In regards to <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://spiritofrecovery.com/exercise.html,">spiritofrecovery.com/exercise.html,</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> <br>
<br>
Yes, there are a group of individuals who do &quot;over-do&quot; their workouts, be it at the gym, or on their own accord elsewhere. There are many differences between an individual that works him, or herself moderately and gains benefits, and another that overdoes their regimen.  A number of things to observe: Is the individual on a routine observed by a qualified weight trainer? Does the individual work out alone, or with a partner or group?  Does the individual make his area unsafe for others, i.e. posing a risk to others.<br>
<br>
Over the course of a weight lifting session, our muscles fatigue. The amount this takes depends on how conditioned the lifter is and the type of workout he, or she undertakes (there are other variables, but those are the big 2) Eventually, the muscles become so fatigued that their level of weight lifting is no longer possible.  There are still, however, other options to pursue when this happens: one can swim, or, can run on a treadmill, for example.<br>
 <br>
&quot;Working out&quot; carries the potential to be addicting on more than one front. Motivation by a team, friend(s) and the opposite sex can compel one to engage in a rigorous workout; the motivation may come from ones self, too. A “well oiled” body has many advantages over a sluggish, out of shape body. Does this mean that we hold one over the other?  Possibly, yes. An in shape body doesn't carry some of the risks that its counterpart does; high blood pressure, risk of heart attacks, diabetes.<br>
<br>
Weight lifting is also an excellent anger and stress sink.  It can take the mind off its current task, being angry or stressed over something in life, and compel it to focus its energy on doing other tasks at hand. What would have been neutral, or detrimental energy has the potential to be transformed into positive energy, and the stress level can be reduced.<br>
<br>
Now, the kicker in weight lifting: <br>
<br>
An individual that hasn't gone to the gym in months is finally guilted enough to go. He's somewhat out of shape, and a bit frustrated with how things are going for him physically; he's putting on a gut.  Because this is a conflict with his prior youth experiences (no gut) he sees this build up as an &quot;enemy&quot; that needs to be removed. What's he do? Well, he over works himself at the gym. He works himself so hard that the next day he has ounces of lactic acid flowing all through his body. The basic movements are difficult and painful, and it will be a few days before he can return to the gym, let alone walk without feeling like he's tearing himself apart.  <br>
<br>
If this individual returns to the gym after a recovering, then he may consider toning his regimen down a notch or three. Pain is a motivating factor - if he wishes pain, over and over, with other possible complication, that’s his choice, even if it's not a rational one. <br>
<br>
<br>
Unlike weight lifting, ones body doesn't necessarily tell you &quot;I'm tired, lets rest&quot; in response to EverQuest. There may be some individuals that say, about 10:00pm &quot;I'm done for tonight.&quot; but that's more likely in response to their circadian rhythm. <br>
<br>
Coordinated body movements in an active environment are at odds with little to no body movement in a resting environment; this means one can engage in EverQuest for longer period of time due to the nature of how the game should be played (in a familiar environment, in a resting position). Of course, one may stretch, and remove themselves from their area of play, but how many individuals do this often. (I believe every 20 minutes is recommended)  There are instances where 12 hour sessions of EverQuest are not uncommon, a good chair helps alleviate support the back while continuing to be comfortable.<br>
<br>
In regards to time allocation,<br>
<br>
Not all humans have a desire to be social with others. EverQuest is allows them to be around other individuals, which may have the same likes / dislikes but it keeps people separate. (no faces, no voices, no body shape - just in-game avatars that show text) For them, EverQuest may be their niche in society, that's fine. <br>
<br>
In regards to friendships online, I wont challenge that many people do hold online friendships as true friendships, but are they the same as real friendships?  Because one isn't presented with a face, or a voice, or in their environment, it's hard to say. I know several people in game that I've known in life, and they come across differently to me than they do in first person.<br>
<br>
Now, if we hold online friendships as equal to real friendships (EverQuest to say, a group of buddies) then which is more important?  Is it okay for you to tell your friends, &quot;sorry, not going out with you guys tonight, gunna kill Aten again and maybe the Emp if he's up.&quot;<br>
<br>
People that don't play EverQuest may wonder, &quot;We're all old friends, and he wont take one night away from his computer over going out and having fun as buds, geesh.&quot;<br>
<br>
How many would willingly trade real life friendships, or relationships for the equal in-game experiences?  I'd bet a few would. Not everyone has pleasant life experiences, some are probably down right horrific, and EverQuest has been a shelter away from that; a posititve experience away from the negativity.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Someone before mentioned that an EverQuest addict would spend less time with his friends so that he could play EverQuest just to fit his guild's &quot;winning attitude.&quot; Why is it okay for a football player to do this and not an EverQuest player?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, that's a tough question. I'll use personal experiences to share in my own light. I joined some of my friends on the football team back in high school. I had friends who didn't like athletics, and some that lived in the weight room every chance they had. Eventually, over time I molded myself into a more agile, faster and stronger individual than I could have been before - my friends helped me get there, as I helped them. Eventually we made it to the playoffs, something few get to go to, and even fewer make it to the state championships. <br>
<br>
Face to face communication, a collection of youths with different background and life experiences, cliques and whatever else are put aside to make one team and face challenges with.<br>
<br>
EverQuest is text to text communication, a collection of people of all ages, with different backgrounds (or similar) that follow their own way and do their own things, be it joining a raiding guild, or work on tradeskills. <br>
<br>
I'm not going to critize people that choose EverQuest over anything else. I too, have played the game since July '99.  It's peoples own choice to do what they will in their lives. <br>
<br>
I see two different points in this post:<br>
<br>
1. Bein Stein being an awful father for shipping his brat of a son away to a boarding school; EverQuest isn't the problem, it's the parenting.<br>
<br>
and, <br>
<br>
2. Is EverQuest addicting?  Do people need to be warned about possible complications that could potentiall arise by playing EverQuest for an extended period of time?<br>
<br>
a. Is a warning needed to inform &quot;at risk&quot; individuals who haven't purchased the product, or <br>
<br>
b. Is a warning not needed, people can commit suicide and fall over dead all they wish; it's their own faults - not ours or SOE's; leave us be.<br>
